title="Forester 4.2">Forester 4.2</fr:link> › new query language</fr:link> › unions and intersections of families of relational queries</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="jonmsterling.xml"
addr="jonmsterling"
title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00WS</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A further primitive query-former is the union or intersection of a certain <fr:em>family</fr:em> of relational queries indexed in the <fr:em>results</fr:em> of a fixed query. These are written as follows:</fr:p><fr:pre><![CDATA[\query/union-fam{q}{mode}{polarity}{relation}
\query/isect-fam{q}{mode}{polarity}{relation}]]></fr:pre><fr:p>The meaning of the above is to first compute the set of trees <fr:code>x,...</fr:code> satisfying the query <fr:code>q</fr:code>, and then take the (union, intersection) of all the induced relational queries <fr:code><![CDATA[\query/rel{mode}{polarity}{relation}{x}]]></fr:code>. With this feature in hand, it becomes possible to compute the full bibliography of a given tree, or find the full list of contributors to a given tree (as opposed to only its immediate contributors).</fr:p><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
